summary: Long time fans will remember this little guy and his rock star relatives! They were definitely overdue for a remake! Once again,...
caption:
Long time fans will remember this little guy and his rock star relatives! They were definitely overdue for a remake! Once again, thanks for @maswartz for giving me the idea for this line waaaaaaaay back in the day!

Type: Normal

Egg group: Monster/ Human-life

Ability: Soundproof/Telepathy

Decibelle (Prodigy pokemon) are very musically gifted Pokemon. They learn  to play new songs very quickly, and master any instruments with ease. However, because they have no fingers playing multiple chords is very difficult for them yet them still manage to somehow play complicated pieces…. somehow. They primarily focus on one instrument during their first stage in evolution, and advance onto the next level when they are ready. When Decibelle strums or hums a tune, dots appear on its belly stripe correlating to the chords.

Type: Normal

Egg Group: Monster/ Human-life

Ability: Soundproof/Telepathy

Ampt (Roadie Pokemon) love nothing more then attention and playing cool, they’ve evolved from playing the humble banjo to a more sophisticated and chill bass. They are constantly causing trouble and act extremely rebellious at this stage. They are always trying to think of new ways to do things that go against the norm and starting anarchy.

Type: Dragon/Normal 

Egg group: Monster/ Human-life

Ability: Soundproof/Telepathy

Konsert (Rapturous Pokemon) Have reached the highest potential of musical ability. Their skills have been said to have influenced hundreds of musicians in the past, and some ancient civilizations have regarded them as the personal Pokemon to their god of music. These Pokemon absolutely live for theatrics and turning everything into a huge show and flexing their advanced guitar skills to make other Pokemon and people swoon. Konsert’s natural instrument- its voice- has an astounding amount of vocal ranges and frequencies,


Signature Move: Reverb [Normal]- Konsert Strums its guitar in a way that damages a single enemy but lowers the special defense and attack of all opponents in the field.

Z-Move: Soul Piercing Ear Splitting Solo [Normal]- Konsert unleashes its full potential in an absolutely radical wailing guitar solo. By shredding his guitar with the confidence and skill that the z-crystal gives him, Konsert unleashes a sound that transcends the physical plain and is said to penetrate straight into and rupture its opponents soul. The solo deals massive super effective damage to all enemies on screen- regardless of ability, type, or states of invulnerability.

Reviewing my personal opinion on every single Pokemon! Yes, all 809 of them!
(Mostly) Daily Uploads, 3 PM EST.

summary: Let’s Talk About Pokemon - Dwebble and Crustle
title: Let’s Talk About Pokemon - Dwebble and Crustle
body:
557: Dwebble

Guys, we talked about this in the Sewaddle review. You can’t just. Go around flashing sickeningly cute junk in my face out of the blue here. Gonna give me a cute overload.

But seriously. Look at this adorable little thing. Seemingly yet another Pokemon to feed into the “the desert is an ocean” thing, here we have a hermit crab that cuts a rock to make a shell out of it. That’s just too precious. It’s got adorable little eyestalks and everything.

You could call this line a parallel to Krabby and Paras at the same time. They’re both crustaceans like Krabby, and they’re both Pokemon carrying things on their back like Paras is. Eventually evolving to carry something much bigger than it is. Difference of course being that Dwebble isn’t being mind-controlled by the rock. At least in theory it isn’t.

Personal Score: 8.5/10

Too good for this world.

558: Crustle

And that name both says it all and is absolute genius. A crustacean that carries a squared-off section of the Earth’s crust on its back. It’s like a Minecraft mob! Or even a creature from Pikmin. Either way, it’s a really fun idea that a totally land-bound hermit crab, instead of finding shells to live in, would just dig out an entire chunk of rock to live in instead. And While I’ve spilled most of what I have to say about it up there with Dwebble, it’s still an absolutely precious Pokemon that’s also cool as hell to boot. What a creative, fun way to make a Bug/Rock type Crustacean Pokemon.

It’s funny that a crab Pokemon ends up being Bug type though! Usually, crustaceans end up just being Water type. Fun fact, crustaceans are more closely related to insects than arachnids are. So, if you wanna aim for realism, if the arachnid Pokemon like Spinarak and Skorupi can fall under the “Bug” type, so too should Pokemon like Krabby, or indeed, Crustle here.

Personal Score: 8.5/10

What a rad idea.

Overall:

Some really cool and cute crusty crustacean monsters. How wonderful!

[Archive]
